## Study Strategies and Time Management

### Weekly Hour Allocation (Flexible)

**September 2025 ‚Äì December 2025:**
- Mathematics (Calculus 1A‚Äì1B): 8‚Äì10 hours/week
- Programming (Python): 4‚Äì6 hours/week
- Physics (Phase 1‚Äì2): 6‚Äì8 hours/week
- **Total:** 18‚Äì24 hours/week

**January 2026 ‚Äì June 2026:**
- Mathematics (Calculus 1C, Multivariable): 8‚Äì10 hours/week
- Neuroscience (Foundation): 5‚Äì7 hours/week
- Physics (Phase 3‚Äì4): 8‚Äì10 hours/week
- Programming (Applied): 2‚Äì3 hours/week
- **Total:** 23‚Äì30 hours/week

**July 2026 ‚Äì May 2027:**
- Mathematics (Differential Equations): 5‚Äì8 hours/week
- Neuroscience (Advanced Computational): 8‚Äì10 hours/week
- Physics (Phase 5‚Äì8, Capstone): 9‚Äì12 hours/week
- **Total:** 22‚Äì30 hours/week

**Adjustment Principle:** Prioritize in order of prerequisite dependency:
1. **Mathematics** (foundation for everything else)
2. **Physics/Engineering** (hands-on application and learning)
3. **Neuroscience** (builds on both math and engineering)
4. **Programming** (support tool across all areas)

---

### Active Learning Methods

1. **Problem Sets:** Complete all assigned problem sets (not optional)‚Äîcritical for retention
2. **Coding:** Implement mathematical concepts in Python and Arduino
3. **Hardware Building:** Physically construct circuits; troubleshoot with oscilloscope
4. **Visualization:** Create plots/animations of calculus, DE, and neural models
5. **Reading:** Supplement lectures with recommended textbooks
6. **Discussion:** Join course forums, online communities, neuroscience study groups
7. **Projects:** Build integrative projects combining multiple courses
8. **Documentation:** Write clear lab notes and technical documentation
9. **Peer Feedback:** Share work with study partners or mentors for critique

---

## Success Metrics

### Mathematics Track
- [ ] Proficiency in differentiation and integration
- [ ] Mastery of multivariable calculus applications
- [ ] Deep understanding of differential equations and their applications
- [ ] Ability to model physical and biological systems mathematically

### Programming Track
- [ ] Fluency in Python for scientific computing (NumPy, SciPy, Matplotlib)
- [ ] Ability to implement mathematical algorithms
- [ ] Competency in Arduino/embedded C programming
- [ ] Ready for advanced neuroscience modeling and biosignal processing

### Physics & Neuroengineering Track
- [ ] Build functioning circuits from foundational electronics through bioamplifiers
- [ ] Design and test signal processing systems on real hardware
- [ ] Record and analyze EEG/EMG biosignals
- [ ] Implement machine learning classifiers on embedded systems
- [ ] Complete professional-grade capstone project (PCB design, validation, documentation)

